==Abstract==

This IIP describes the OP_CHECKLOCKTIMEVERIFY (CLTV) opcode which allows a transaction output to be made unspendable until a specified block height or time. It is adapted from BIP 65 for INTcoin.

==Motivation==

Time-locked transactions enable important use cases:

* '''Payment Channels''': Refund transactions that become valid after a timeout
* '''Escrow''': Funds locked until a future date
* '''Inheritance''': Coins accessible by heirs after a delay
* '''Hash Time-Locked Contracts (HTLCs)''': Foundation of Lightning Network

Without CLTV, nLockTime can be modified by the spender, providing no guarantee to other parties.

==Specification==

===Opcode Definition===

<pre>
OP_CHECKLOCKTIMEVERIFY = 0xb1
</pre>

When executed:

# If the stack is empty, fail
# If the top stack item is negative, fail
# If the top stack item is greater than or equal to 500000000 and nLockTime is less than 500000000, or vice versa, fail
# If the top stack item is greater than the transaction's nLockTime, fail
# If the transaction input's nSequence is 0xffffffff, fail
# Otherwise, continue (the stack is not modified)

===Semantics===

The top stack value represents either:
* '''Block height''': If < 500000000
* '''Unix timestamp''': If >= 500000000

The transaction's nLockTime must be of the same type and be >= the stack value.

===Script Example===

Time-locked output (spendable after block 100000):

<pre>
<100000> OP_CHECKLOCKTIMEVERIFY OP_DROP <pubkey> OP_CHECKSIG_DILITHIUM
</pre>

To spend, the transaction must have:
* nLockTime >= 100000
* nSequence < 0xffffffff on the input

===Pseudocode===

<pre>
def op_checklocktimeverify(stack, tx, input_index):
    if len(stack) < 1:
        return False

    locktime = stack[-1]  # Don't pop

    if locktime < 0:
        return False

    # Check type match (height vs time)
    LOCKTIME_THRESHOLD = 500000000
    if ((locktime >= LOCKTIME_THRESHOLD) != (tx.nLockTime >= LOCKTIME_THRESHOLD)):
        return False

    if locktime > tx.nLockTime:
        return False

    if tx.vin[input_index].nSequence == 0xffffffff:
        return False

    return True
</pre>

==Rationale==

===Why Not Pop?===

CLTV leaves the value on the stack (requiring OP_DROP after) to allow:
* Verification without modifying stack state
* Combining with other checks on the same value

===Sequence Check===

nSequence must be < 0xffffffff because:
* nSequence = 0xffffffff disables nLockTime
* This would make the CLTV check meaningless
* Failing in this case catches script errors

===Type Mixing Prevention===

Comparing height to time would be nonsensical:
* Block 500000000 will never exist
* Timestamp 100000 was in 1970

==Backwards Compatibility==

OP_CHECKLOCKTIMEVERIFY was previously OP_NOP2. Scripts using OP_NOP2 will:
* Continue to work (CLTV is a soft fork restriction)
* Now have semantic meaning if a value is on the stack

